# Frontend: Components & UX

## Component-Based Architecture

- Build the UI from **small, single-responsibility components**; compose pages from them.
- Prefer **functional components** with hooks; keep components focused and testable.
- Colocate component-specific styles and types next to the component when they aren’t shared.

## Reusable Components

- Extract repeated UI and behavior into **shared components** (e.g. `Button`, `Card`, `Input`, `Modal`).
- Design components to be **configurable via props** (variants, size, disabled, etc.), not hardcoded.
- Place shared components in a dedicated folder (e.g. `components/` or `component/`) and use them across pages.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD – one-off, not reusable
<div className="rounded bg-blue-500 p-2 text-white" onClick={...}>Submit</div>

// ✅ GOOD – reusable, configurable
<Button variant="primary" size="md" onClick={onSubmit}>Submit</Button>
```

## Attractive Design & Good UX

- Use a **consistent design system**: spacing scale, typography, and a limited color palette.
- Prefer **clear hierarchy**: headings, contrast, and whitespace so content is scannable.
- Give **immediate feedback**: loading states, disabled states, and success/error messages for actions.
- Keep **interactions obvious**: visible focus states, hover feedback, and clear primary actions.
- Ensure **accessibility**: semantic HTML, ARIA when needed, keyboard navigation, and sufficient color contrast.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD – no feedback, flat layout
<button onClick={submit}>Save</button>

// ✅ GOOD – loading state, hierarchy, accessible
<Button
  onClick={submit}
  disabled={isSubmitting}
  aria-busy={isSubmitting}
>
  {isSubmitting ? 'Saving…' : 'Save'}
</Button>
```
